So people moved onto street heroin, which is much more dangerous since - unlike a pill that’s made in a carefully controlled modern manufacturing plant - you have no idea what you’re getting. Then they cracked down on heroin, so the drug cartels moved into fentanyl and fentanyl analogues, which are orders of magnitude more potent and therefore far easier to smuggle.

Gee, it’s almost like prohibition doesn’t work, and in fact only makes the problem worse. Something everyone acknowledges vis-a-vis the USA’s short-lived, ham-fisted attempt at alcohol prohibition, but for some reason there’s this cognitive dissonance when it comes to the ham-fisted attempt at prohibition of other drugs.

textDisplay: I've been living in Mexico for almost 30 years and what this lady says in 1:50 this is completely false, you can't buy any drug in mexico without a prescription on a pharmacy. You can buy some drugs like Tylenol (Paracetamol), Ibuprofen or Claritin (Loratadin) without a prescription like many other OTC drugs in the US, but If you need psicotropicos like Xanax (Alprazolam) you need to get a prescription from a Neurologist or Psychiatrist and the pharmacy is going to take the rx. Aswell is really rare that doctors in Mexico prescribe you hard painkillers for anything else than cancer or a very hard affliction, for example if you brake a bone, you'll be sent home with some Tylenol, ibuprofen or Ketorolac, that why there is not heroin epidemic in Mexico. So no, you can't buy any prescription drugs in Mexico from a regular Pharmacy without the proper prescription, you need to go to the black market to get them and that is no different from buying drugs in any other part of the world.
